{{Infobox person | name = Shri Paramhans Advaitanand Ji Maharaj | image = Paramhans Dyal Ji.jpg | caption = | birth_date = 1846 | birth_place = Chapra | death_date = 1919 | known_for = [[ Advait Mat]] | successor = Swami [[Swarupanand ]] Ji Maharaj }}
'''Shri Swami Paramhans Advaitanand Ji Maharaj''' , also known as '''Shri Paramhans Dayal Ji'''(born Shri '''Ram Yaad'''), son of Shri Tulsi Das Ji Pathak, was born in Chapra, [[Bihar]], India. Shri Paramhans Dayal Ji is also known as the "First Spiritual Master" of the [[Advait Mat|Shri Paramhans Advait Mat]] lineage or Parampara. He initiated the "Second Master", [[Swarupanand|Shri Swami Swarupanand Ji Maharaj]] in the early 1900s.<ref>Sri Swami Sar Shabdanand Ji, ''Shri Swarup Darshan'' (1998), pp. 17–59. New Delhi: Sar Shabd Mission.</ref>
He was born on the day of [[Rama Navami|Ram navami]] and was therefore named as "Ram Yaad ". His father was famous scholar Pandit Tulsi Pathak. His mother died a few months after his birth and he was brought up by his father's disciple Lala Narhari Prasad. Shri Narhari Prasad arranged for his education. Shri Ramyaad gained good knowledge of Sanskrit, Hindi, Arabic and Pharisee which were the prominent languages of that time. At the age of five, his father Shri Tulsiram ji died.<ref>''Shri Paramhansa Advait Mat: A life sketch of the Illustrious Master of the Mat'' (1975), Shri Anandpur Trust</ref>
Shri Ramyaad attended satsangs which used to happen at his house and which created a great impact on his mind. Paramhans Swamiji gave diksha to him and taught him about Brahma Vidya. When he was 11 years old, Narhari Prasad died and after some years wife of narhari prasad also died. He was the only rightful successor of the both families but at the age of 16, he left his home and went to the forests of Bihar for meditation. He was in Jaipur in 1883, where he met the 90 years old Swami [[Anandpuri]] ji, who taught him the [[Kriyā|Kriya]] of [[Pranayama|Pranayaam]] and [[Yoga]]. He reportedly wrote in Urdu on a paper: "Accept Paramhans Ram Yaad". He named him as his spiritual succcessor to his seat but Shri Paramhans Dayal Ji renounced the seat too. In his view, fame for a fakir was a fall from grace.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brahmavidyalayaashram.in/ancestry/adwaitanandji/|title=Shri Shri 1008 Shri Swami Adwaitanandji Maharaj Paramhans|last=|first=|date=|website=Brahma Vidyalaya & Ashram|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
Shri Paramahans Dyal Ji travelled from place to place and carried the message of Sahaj Yoga, Bhakti and service unto humanity to one and all. Shri Paramhansa Dayal Ji stayed at Jaipur for a considerable time and started the work of spiritual preachings and of uplifting the people there. The number of followers there was quite large. Being a wandering monk, He covered Bihar, Uttar Pradesh, Odisha, Madhya Pradesh, Rajasthan, etc. to teach 'Sahajyoga' and 'Bhakti' to the people there .
The ashrams (temples) founded by Shri Paramahans Dyal Ji were called '''''Krishana Dwaras'''''. The ashrams in [[India]] with the name Advait-Swarup Ashram, Paramhans Satyarthi Dham, Shri Anandpur Satsang Ashram are also related to him and [[Advait Mat|Shri Paramhans Advait Mat]].
Shri Paramahans Dyal Ji attained [[Nirvana]] in July, 1919 after transferring succession of the seat to [[Swarupanand|Swami Swarupanand ji]]. He had promised to his devotee Seth Amirchand, living in Karachi that he would sacrifice his body and take Samadhi at his place. The samadhi temple of Paramhans Dyal ji is now in [[Pakistan]].The temple was damaged by extremists in 1997. The Supreme Court of Pakistan ordered the provincial government to reconstruct the damaged Hindu Temple on April 4, 2015. The Samadhi Temple of Shri Paramhans Dyal Ji has been re-constructed by Shri Anandpur Trust.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/bihar/patna/news/BIH-PAT-HMU-gurudev-shri-paramhans-dayal-ji-maharaj-news-hindi-5379694-PHO.html|title=इस संत को पूजता था पूरा पाकिस्तान, पर अपने शहर में ही हैं अनजान|last=|first=|date=Jul 24, 2016|work=Dainik Bhaskar|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://naidunia.jagran.com/national-indian-sant-gets-his-due-respect-in-pakistan-355646|title=Indian saint wins respect in Pakistan|last=|first=|date=24 Apr 2015|work=Naidunia Jagran|access-date=}}</ref><ref>https://www.shrianandpur.org</ref>
