{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}} {{Use Australian English|date=January 2017}} '''Mark Johnston''' is an Australian philosopher, who has spent his entire career at [[Princeton University]].
== Biography and career == Johnston is the Walter Cerf Professor of Philosophy at [[Princeton University]], where he has taught since earning his Ph.D there in 1984. His dissertation, "Particulars and Persistence,"<ref>http://philpapers.org/rec/JOHPAP-15</ref> was directed by [[Saul Kripke]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philosophy.princeton.edu/content/mark-johnston|title=Mark Johnston|work=princeton.edu}}</ref> A native of Australia, Johnston was "educated by Jesuits and briefly considered taking priestly orders before opting for a PhD in philosophy instead."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.booksandculture.com/articles/2012/mayjun/savinggod.html|title=Saving God from "Saving God."|work=Books and Culture}}</ref>
Johnston is also the Senior Academic Advisor to the Marc Sanders Foundation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marcsandersfoundation.org/about/whos-who/|title=Who’s Who|work=marcsandersfoundation.org}}</ref> which awards prizes for the best work in various areas of philosophy, such as [[metaphysics]], [[philosophy of religion]], and [[ethics]].
== Philosophical work ==
Johnston has written many articles on topics in [[metaphysics]], [[philosophy of mind]], [[philosophical logic]], and [[metaethics]] and, more recently, two books in philosophy of religion, ''Saving God: Religion After Idolatry'' (Princeton University Press, 2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://press.princeton.edu/titles/8978.html|title=Johnston, M.: Saving God: Religion after Idolatry. (eBook and Paperback)|work=princeton.edu}}</ref> and ''Surviving Death'' (Princeton University Press, 2010).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://press.princeton.edu/titles/9151.html|title=Johnston, M.: Surviving Death (eBook and Paperback).|work=princeton.edu}}</ref> The literary critic [[James Wood (critic)|James Wood]] picked ''Saving God'' as one of the top non-fiction books of 2009 in ''[[The New Yorker]]''. <ref>http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/james-wood-on-the-books-of-2009</ref>
==Selected articles== *"Human Beings," ''Journal of Philosophy'' 84 (1987): 59-83. *"Dispositional Theories of Value," ''Proceedings of the Aristotelian Society'' 63 (1989): 89-174 (with [[David K. Lewis]] and [[Michael A. Smith]]) *"Reasons and Reductionism," ''Philosophical Review'' (1992): 589-618. *"Constitution is Not Identity," ''Mind'' 101 (1992): 89-106. *"Manifest Kinds," ''Journal of Philosophy'' 94 (1997): 564-583. *"The Obscure Object of Hallucination," ''Philosophical Studies'' 120 (2004): 113-83. *"Hylomorphism," ''Journal of Philosophy'' 103 (2006): 652-698.<ref>http://philpapers.org/profile/4661</ref>
