{{BLP primary sources|date=May 2012}} '''Walter Sinnott-Armstrong''' (born 1955) is an [[United States|American]] philosopher. He specializes in [[ethics]], [[epistemology]], and more recently in [[neuroethics]], the [[philosophy of law]], and the [[philosophy of psychology|philosophy of cognitive science]]. He is the Chauncey Stillman Professor of Practical Ethics in the Department of Philosophy and the Kenan Institute for Ethics at [[Duke University]].<ref name="Bio">{{cite web|url=http://sites.duke.edu/wsa/ |title=Bio |publisher=www.duke.edu |accessdate=2012-01-23}}</ref> He earned his Ph.D. from [[Yale University]] under the supervision of [[Robert Fogelin]] and [[Ruth Barcan Marcus]], and taught for many years at [[Dartmouth College]], before moving to Duke.<ref>http://sites.duke.edu/wsa/files/2011/05/WSA-CV-2012.pdf</ref>
His ''Moral Skepticisms'' (2006) defends the view that we do not have fully adequate responses to [[moral skepticism|the moral skeptic]]. It also defends a [[coherentism|coherentist]] moral epistemology, which he has defended for decades. His ''Morality Without God?'' (2009) endorses the moral philosophy of his former colleague [[Bernard Gert]] as an alternative to [[ethics in religion|religious]] views of [[morality]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2012}}
In 1999, he debated [[William Lane Craig]] in a debate titled "God? A Debate Between A Christian and An Atheist".<ref>http://commonsenseatheism.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/Craig-Sinnott-Armstrong-God-A-Debate-between-a-Christian-and-an-Atheist.pdf</ref>
Walter Sinnott-Armstrong argues that God is not only not essential to morality, but moral behaviour should be independent of religion. A separate entity, one could say. He strongly disagrees with several core ideas: that atheists are immoral people; that any society will become like ''Lord of the Flies'' if it becomes too secular; that without morality being laid out in front of us, like a commandment, we have no reason to be moral; that absolute moral standards require the existence of a God.
Walter Sinnott-Armstrong is a proponent of [[Contrastivism]], the idea that all claims of reasons are relative to contrast classes.<ref>A Contrastivist Manifesto, Walter Sinnott‐Armstrong, Social Epistemology, Vol. 22, Iss. 3, 2008, [https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/02691720802546120 DOI:10.1080/02691720802546120]</ref> According to him, ''"[the contrastivist] approach applies to explanation (reasons why things happen), moral philosophy (reasons for action), and epistemology (reasons for belief), and it illuminates moral dilemmas, [[free will]], and the [[New_riddle_of_induction|grue paradox]]."''
==Publications== Some of his notable publications include:
* ''Moral Dilemmas'', Basil Blackwell, 1988. * ''God? A Debate between a Christian and an Atheist'', William Lane Craig and Walter Sinnott-Armstrong, New York: Oxford University Press, 2003. * ''Moral Skepticisms'', Oxford University Press, 2006. * editor, ''Moral Psychology'' (Five Volumes), MIT Press, 2008. * ''Morality Without God?'', Oxford University Press, 2009. * ''Think Again: How to Reason and Argue'', Oxford University Press / Penguin Books, 2018.
